block content

  //- Article Hero
  header.page-hero
    .container.px-4.px-lg-5
      .row.justify-content-center
        .col-lg-8
          nav(aria-label="breadcrumb")
            ol.breadcrumb.mb-3
              li.breadcrumb-item
                a(href="/") Home
              li.breadcrumb-item
                a(href="/blog.html") Blog
              li.breadcrumb-item.active(aria-current="page") How to Get Sober in Spokane
          h1 How to Get Sober in Spokane, WA: A Step-by-Step Local Guide to Recovery
          p.lead You don't need to leave Spokane to find world-class recovery support. Here is exactly how to start—from day one through your first year sober.
          .hero-badges
            .hero-badge
              i.bi.bi-calendar3
              span April 2026
            .hero-badge
              i.bi.bi-clock
              span 12 min read

  //- Article Body
  section.page-section
    .container.px-4.px-lg-5
      .row.justify-content-center
        .col-lg-8

          //- TL;DR
          .card.border-0.bg-light.p-4.mb-4
            h5.fw-bold TL;DR / Key Takeaways
            ul.mb-0
              li
                strong Spokane has the full continuum of care
                |  — from medical detox and residential rehab to outpatient therapy, MAT clinics, and free peer support groups.
              li
                strong You can start for $0.
                |  Apple Health (Medicaid) covers detox and rehab. Apply at any CHAS clinic for same-day coverage.
              li
                strong Support groups meet daily.
                |  AA, NA, SMART Recovery, Celebrate Recovery, and Refuge Recovery all have active Spokane chapters.
              li
                strong Safe housing exists.
                |  Oxford Houses, Union Gospel Mission, Catholic Charities, and VOA all provide sober living environments.
              li
                strong You are not alone.
                |  Call 988 for crisis support, 2-1-1 for resource navigation, or visit our Resource Directory anytime.

          //- Quick Definition
          h2.mt-2 What Does "Getting Sober in Spokane" Actually Mean?
          p.lead
            strong Getting sober in Spokane
            |  means accessing the Inland Northwest's network of medical detox facilities, evidence-based treatment centers, free peer support groups, and sober housing programs to safely stop using substances and build a sustainable, drug- and alcohol-free life — all without leaving your community.

          //- Table of Contents
          .mb-5.p-4.bg-light.rounded
            h4.h5 Table of Contents
            ul.list-unstyled.mb-0
              li.mb-2: a(href="#step-1") Step 1: Acknowledge the Problem & Reach Out
              li.mb-2: a(href="#step-2") Step 2: Get a Medical Assessment
              li.mb-2: a(href="#step-3") Step 3: Medical Detox — Safely Stop Using
              li.mb-2: a(href="#step-4") Step 4: Choose Your Treatment Level
              li.mb-2: a(href="#step-5") Step 5: Secure Sober Housing
              li.mb-2: a(href="#step-6") Step 6: Join a Support Group
              li.mb-2: a(href="#step-7") Step 7: Build Your Sober Life
              li.mb-2: a(href="#step-8") Step 8: Plan for Relapse Prevention
              li.mb-2: a(href="#comparison") Treatment Comparison Table
              li.mb-2: a(href="#mistakes") Common Mistakes to Avoid
              li.mb-2: a(href="#faq") Frequently Asked Questions
              li.mb-0: a(href="#conclusion") Your Next Step

          hr.my-5

          //- Intro
          p Getting sober is one of the most courageous decisions you will ever make — and one of the hardest. The good news? Spokane, Washington is one of the strongest recovery communities in the Pacific Northwest.
          p Whether you're battling alcohol, opioids, methamphetamine, or any other substance, Spokane has the infrastructure, the people, and the programs to meet you exactly where you are. This guide walks you through each step of how to get sober in Spokane — from your first honest conversation to your first year of recovery.

          //- Step 1
          h2#step-1.mt-5
            i.bi.bi-1-circle-fill.text-primary.me-2
            | Step 1: Acknowledge the Problem & Reach Out
          p The first step isn't treatment — it's honesty. Admitting you have a problem with drugs or alcohol is the foundation everything else is built on.
          p
            strong What to do:
            |  Tell one person you trust. Call a crisis line. Walk into a meeting. There is no wrong way to start.
          .card.border-start.border-4.border-primary.bg-light.p-3.mb-4
            p.mb-0
              i.bi.bi-telephone-fill.text-primary.me-2
              strong Immediate help:
              |  Call #[a(href='tel:988') 988] (24/7 Suicide & Crisis Lifeline), #[a(href='tel:+18772661818') (877) 266-1818] (Spokane Regional Crisis Line), or #[a(href='tel:+18667891511') 1-866-789-1511] (WA Recovery Help Line).
          p
            strong Pro Tip:
            |  If you're not ready to talk on the phone, text HOME to 741741 to reach the Crisis Text Line — it's free, confidential, and available 24/7.
          p
            strong Common Pitfall:
            |  Waiting until you "hit rock bottom." There is no prerequisite for asking for help. The best time to get sober is right now.

          //- Step 2
          h2#step-2.mt-5
            i.bi.bi-2-circle-fill.text-primary.me-2
            | Step 2: Get a Medical Assessment
          p Before you stop using any substance, a medical professional should evaluate your situation. Withdrawal from alcohol and benzodiazepines can be life-threatening without medical supervision.
          p
            strong What to do:
            |  Call one of these Spokane providers for a substance use assessment:
          ul
            li
              strong STARS (Spokane Treatment & Recovery Services):
              |  #[a(href='tel:+15095707250') (509) 570-7250] — walk-in assessments, medical detox, residential treatment.
            li
              strong Frontier Behavioral Health:
              |  #[a(href='tel:+15098384651') (509) 838-4651] — mental health and SUD assessments, sliding fee scale.
            li
              strong Spokane Falls Recovery Center:
              |  #[a(href='tel:+18449622775') (844) 962-2775] — detox, residential, and outpatient assessments.
          p
            strong Why it matters:
            |  Your assessment determines the safest level of care. Some people need medical detox first; others can begin outpatient therapy immediately.
          p
            strong Pro Tip:
            |  If you don't have insurance, go to any #[a(href='https://chas.org', target='_blank', rel='noopener') CHAS Health] clinic. Their navigators can enroll you in Apple Health (Medicaid) on the spot — often with same-day activation.

          //- Step 3
          h2#step-3.mt-5
            i.bi.bi-3-circle-fill.text-primary.me-2
            | Step 3: Medical Detox — Safely Stop Using
          p Medical detox is the supervised process of clearing drugs or alcohol from your body while managing withdrawal symptoms. It typically lasts 3–10 days depending on the substance.
          p
            strong Spokane detox facilities:
          .table-responsive
            table.table.table-bordered.table-striped
              thead.table-dark
                tr
                  th Facility
                  th Phone
                  th Detox Type
                  th Insurance
              tbody
                tr
                  td STARS – Cowley St
                  td: a(href='tel:+15095707250') (509) 570-7250
                  td Medical detox, crisis stabilization
                  td Apple Health, most insurance
                tr
                  td Inland Northwest Behavioral Health
                  td: a(href='tel:+15099921888') (509) 992-1888
                  td 100-bed psychiatric & medical detox
                  td Most insurance accepted
                tr
                  td Royal Life Centers at Spokane Heights
                  td: a(href='tel:+15093689735') (509) 368-9735
                  td Medical detox, personalized care
                  td Private insurance, payment plans
                tr
                  td Spokane Falls Recovery Center
                  td: a(href='tel:+18449622775') (844) 962-2775
                  td Detox, residential transition
                  td Most insurance accepted
          p
            strong Common Pitfall:
            |  Trying to detox from alcohol or benzos at home. Alcohol withdrawal can cause fatal seizures. Always consult a medical professional first.

          //- Step 4
          h2#step-4.mt-5
            i.bi.bi-4-circle-fill.text-primary.me-2
            | Step 4: Choose Your Treatment Level
          p After detox, the next step is structured treatment. Spokane offers every level of the #[a(href='/blog/inpatient-vs-outpatient-rehab-spokane.html') ASAM continuum of care]:

          .row.gx-4.gy-4.mb-4
            .col-md-6
              .card.h-100.border-0.shadow-sm
                .card-body
                  h5.text-primary
                    i.bi.bi-building.me-2
                    | Residential (Inpatient)
                  p Live at the facility 24/7 for 30–90 days. Best for severe addiction, unstable housing, or co-occurring disorders.
                  ul.small
                    li Royal Life Centers — #[a(href='tel:+15093689735') (509) 368-9735]
                    li Pioneer Pathways — #[a(href='tel:+15093252358') (509) 325-2358]
                    li SPARC — #[a(href='tel:+15093273741') (509) 327-3741]
                    li Karen's House (women) — #[a(href='tel:+15095707250') (509) 570-7250]
            .col-md-6
              .card.h-100.border-0.shadow-sm
                .card-body
                  h5.text-success
                    i.bi.bi-calendar-week.me-2
                    | Outpatient (IOP/OP)
                  p Attend therapy sessions 3–5 days per week while living at home or in sober housing. Best for stable housing and moderate addiction.
                  ul.small
                    li Rebuilt Treatment — #[a(href='tel:+15093854600') (509) 385-4600]
                    li Riverside Recovery — #[a(href='tel:+15093285234') (509) 328-5234]
                    li CAT Spokane — #[a(href='tel:+15092905026') (509) 290-5026]
                    li Recovery Cafe — #[a(href='tel:+15096241442') (509) 624-1442]

          .card.border-start.border-4.border-warning.bg-light.p-3.mb-4
            p.mb-0
              i.bi.bi-lightbulb-fill.text-warning.me-2
              strong Expert Note:
              |  Research consistently shows that longer treatment produces better outcomes. If possible, commit to at least 90 days of structured care. Many Spokane programs offer extended tracks specifically because of this evidence.

          //- Step 5
          h2#step-5.mt-5
            i.bi.bi-5-circle-fill.text-primary.me-2
            | Step 5: Secure Sober Housing
          p Stable, sober housing is one of the strongest predictors of long-term recovery success. Spokane has multiple options:
          ul
            li
              strong Oxford Houses:
              |  Self-governed, democratically run sober living homes. No time limit. Search at #[a(href='https://oxfordhouse.org', target='_blank', rel='noopener') oxfordhouse.org].
            li
              strong Union Gospel Mission:
              |  Free emergency shelter and long-term recovery program with housing at 1224 E Trent Ave — #[a(href='tel:+15095358510') (509) 535-8510].
            li
              strong Catholic Charities – St. Margaret's Shelter:
              |  Family transitional housing for up to 2 years — #[a(href='tel:+15096249788') (509) 624-9788].
            li
              strong Revive Reentry Services:
              |  Transitional housing for individuals leaving incarceration — #[a(href='tel:+15093191068') (509) 319-1068].
            li
              strong Spokane Housing Authority:
              |  Affordable housing and voucher programs — #[a(href='tel:+15093282953') (509) 328-2953].
          p For the full directory, visit our #[a(href='/shelter-housing.html') Shelter & Housing Resources] page.

          //- Step 6
          h2#step-6.mt-5
            i.bi.bi-6-circle-fill.text-primary.me-2
            | Step 6: Join a Support Group
          p Peer support is the backbone of lasting recovery. Spokane has active chapters of every major recovery fellowship:

          .table-responsive
            table.table.table-bordered.table-striped
              thead.table-dark
                tr
                  th Program
                  th Approach
                  th Spokane Location
                  th Contact
              tbody
                tr
                  td Alcoholics Anonymous (AA)
                  td 12-Step, spiritual
                  td Alano Club, 1700 W 7th Ave
                  td: a(href='https://aaspokane.org', target='_blank', rel='noopener') aaspokane.org
                tr
                  td Narcotics Anonymous (NA)
                  td 12-Step, spiritual
                  td 103 E Indiana Ave + others
                  td: a(href='https://na.org', target='_blank', rel='noopener') na.org
                tr
                  td SMART Recovery
                  td Science-based, CBT
                  td Alano Club, Tue & Thu 6 PM
                  td: a(href='https://smartrecovery.org', target='_blank', rel='noopener') smartrecovery.org
                tr
                  td Celebrate Recovery
                  td Faith-based, 12-Step
                  td Family of Faith, Fri 7 PM + others
                  td Multiple churches
                tr
                  td Refuge Recovery
                  td Buddhist-inspired, meditation
                  td Souls Center, 707 N Cedar St
                  td Wed 1 PM
                tr
                  td Al-Anon / Alateen
                  td Family support
                  td 1700 W 7th Ave, Suite 100
                  td: a(href='tel:+15094562125') (509) 456-2125

          p
            strong Pro Tip:
            |  Try at least 6 different meetings before deciding a program isn't for you. Every meeting has its own personality. Our #[a(href='/sponsor-finder.html') Sponsor Finder] can connect you with a local guide.

          //- Step 7
          h2#step-7.mt-5
            i.bi.bi-7-circle-fill.text-primary.me-2
            | Step 7: Build Your Sober Life in Spokane
          p Recovery isn't just about stopping substances — it's about building a life you don't want to escape from. Spokane makes this possible:

          .row.gx-4.gy-4.mb-4
            .col-md-4
              .card.h-100.border-0.shadow-sm.text-center.p-4
                i.bi.bi-briefcase-fill.fs-1.text-primary.mb-3
                h5 Employment
                p.small WorkSource Spokane, Goodwill, and Pioneer Human Services offer job placement for people in recovery.
                a.small(href='/employment-skills.html') View Resources →
            .col-md-4
              .card.h-100.border-0.shadow-sm.text-center.p-4
                i.bi.bi-people-fill.fs-1.text-success.mb-3
                h5 Sober Activities
                p.small Reclaim Project, Centennial Trail hikes, sober sports leagues, coffee meetups, and volunteer opportunities.
                a.small(href='/community-engagement-sober-activities.html') View Activities →
            .col-md-4
              .card.h-100.border-0.shadow-sm.text-center.p-4
                i.bi.bi-heart-pulse-fill.fs-1.text-danger.mb-3
                h5 Mental Health
                p.small Frontier Behavioral Health, CHAS, and NAMI Spokane offer ongoing counseling and peer support.
                a.small(href='/medical-mental-health.html') View Services →

          //- Step 8
          h2#step-8.mt-5
            i.bi.bi-8-circle-fill.text-primary.me-2
            | Step 8: Plan for Relapse Prevention
          p Relapse is not failure — it's a common part of recovery. The key is having a plan before it happens.
          ul
            li
              strong Know your triggers:
              |  People, places, emotions, and situations that activate cravings. Write them down.
            li
              strong Build your team:
              |  Sponsor, therapist, sober friends, crisis numbers saved in your phone.
            li
              strong Attend meetings regularly:
              |  People who attend support groups consistently have significantly better long-term outcomes.
            li
              strong Have a crisis plan:
              |  If you relapse, call your sponsor, go to a meeting, or call 988 immediately. Don't isolate.
          p For a deeper dive, read our guide on #[a(href='/blog/why-do-people-relapse.html') why people relapse and how to prevent it].

          hr.my-5

          //- Comparison Table
          h2#comparison.mt-5
            i.bi.bi-table.text-primary.me-2
            | Spokane Treatment Options at a Glance
          .table-responsive
            table.table.table-bordered.table-striped
              thead.table-dark
                tr
                  th Level of Care
                  th Duration
                  th Best For
                  th Cost with Apple Health
                  th Spokane Providers
              tbody
                tr
                  td Medical Detox
                  td 3–10 days
                  td Alcohol, opioid, benzo withdrawal
                  td $0
                  td STARS, Inland NW BH, Royal Life Centers
                tr
                  td Residential (Inpatient)
                  td 30–90 days
                  td Severe addiction, unstable housing
                  td $0
                  td Royal Life Centers, Pioneer Pathways, SPARC
                tr
                  td Partial Hospitalization (PHP)
                  td 2–6 weeks
                  td Step-down from inpatient
                  td $0
                  td Rebuilt Treatment, Providence RISE
                tr
                  td Intensive Outpatient (IOP)
                  td 6–12 weeks
                  td Moderate addiction, stable housing
                  td $0
                  td Riverside Recovery, Rebuilt, Spokane Falls RC
                tr
                  td Standard Outpatient
                  td Ongoing
                  td Maintenance, relapse prevention
                  td $0
                  td CAT Spokane, Frontier BH, CHAS
                tr
                  td MAT (Medication-Assisted)
                  td Ongoing
                  td Opioid/alcohol cravings
                  td $0
                  td Ideal Option, Spokane CTC
                tr
                  td Peer Support Groups
                  td Ongoing
                  td Community, accountability
                  td Free
                  td AA, NA, SMART, Celebrate Recovery

          hr.my-5

          //- Common Mistakes
          h2#mistakes.mt-5
            i.bi.bi-x-octagon-fill.text-danger.me-2
            | 7 Common Mistakes When Getting Sober in Spokane
          ol.mt-4
            li.mb-3
              strong Mistake: Trying to detox from alcohol or benzos without medical help.
              br
              strong Fix:
              |  Always get a medical assessment first. Call STARS at (509) 570-7250 or go to any ER.
            li.mb-3
              strong Mistake: Thinking you need to leave Spokane for "real" rehab.
              br
              strong Fix:
              |  Spokane has nationally accredited facilities. Royal Life Centers, STARS, and Pioneer Pathways provide top-tier care.
            li.mb-3
              strong Mistake: Going straight home after detox without a plan.
              br
              strong Fix:
              |  Step down into residential treatment or IOP, secure sober housing, and connect with a support group before going home.
            li.mb-3
              strong Mistake: Isolating from everyone during early recovery.
              br
              strong Fix:
              |  Attend a meeting, call our #[a(href='/chat.html') live community chat], or visit Recovery Cafe for free meals and connection.
            li.mb-3
              strong Mistake: Not applying for Apple Health because you think you earn "too much."
              br
              strong Fix:
              |  Income limits are higher than most people think. Let a CHAS navigator run the numbers for you.
            li.mb-3
              strong Mistake: Paying an online "treatment placement" service.
              br
              strong Fix:
              |  These are often predatory. Use our free #[a(href='/resource-directory.html') Resource Directory] or call the WA Recovery Help Line at 1-866-789-1511.
            li.mb-3
              strong Mistake: Giving up after a relapse.
              br
              strong Fix:
              |  Relapse is a common part of recovery, not a death sentence. Call your sponsor, go to a meeting, or call 988. Start again.

          hr.my-5

          //- FAQ
          h2#faq.mt-5
            i.bi.bi-question-circle.text-primary.me-2
            | Frequently Asked Questions About Getting Sober in Spokane

          .accordion.mt-4#faqAccordion
            .accordion-item
              h2.accordion-header#faqH1
                button.accordion-button(type="button" data-bs-toggle="collapse" data-bs-target="#faqC1" aria-expanded="true" aria-controls="faqC1")
                  | How do I get sober in Spokane if I have no money?
              #faqC1.accordion-collapse.collapse.show(aria-labelledby="faqH1" data-bs-parent="#faqAccordion")
                .accordion-body
                  | Spokane has extensive free resources. Apply for Apple Health (Medicaid) at any CHAS clinic for same-day coverage. State-funded treatment is available at STARS and Frontier Behavioral Health. Free shelter is available at Union Gospel Mission, House of Charity, and Hope House. Call Washington 2-1-1 for immediate referrals.

            .accordion-item
              h2.accordion-header#faqH2
                button.accordion-button.collapsed(type="button" data-bs-toggle="collapse" data-bs-target="#faqC2" aria-expanded="false" aria-controls="faqC2")
                  | What is the first step to getting sober?
              #faqC2.accordion-collapse.collapse(aria-labelledby="faqH2" data-bs-parent="#faqAccordion")
                .accordion-body
                  | The safest first step is a medical assessment. Call the Spokane Regional Crisis Line at (877) 266-1818 or visit an ER if in active withdrawal. For non-emergency situations, contact STARS at (509) 570-7250 or Frontier Behavioral Health at (509) 838-4651 for a substance use assessment.

            .accordion-item
              h2.accordion-header#faqH3
                button.accordion-button.collapsed(type="button" data-bs-toggle="collapse" data-bs-target="#faqC3" aria-expanded="false" aria-controls="faqC3")
                  | Can I detox at home safely?
              #faqC3.accordion-collapse.collapse(aria-labelledby="faqH3" data-bs-parent="#faqAccordion")
                .accordion-body
                  | It depends on the substance. Alcohol and benzodiazepine withdrawal can be life-threatening and should always involve medical supervision. Opioid withdrawal is intensely uncomfortable but rarely fatal. Spokane offers medical detox at STARS, Inland Northwest Behavioral Health, and Royal Life Centers. If unsure, call 988 or your doctor.

            .accordion-item
              h2.accordion-header#faqH4
                button.accordion-button.collapsed(type="button" data-bs-toggle="collapse" data-bs-target="#faqC4" aria-expanded="false" aria-controls="faqC4")
                  | Are there AA or NA meetings in Spokane?
              #faqC4.accordion-collapse.collapse(aria-labelledby="faqH4" data-bs-parent="#faqAccordion")
                .accordion-body
                  | Yes. Spokane has hundreds of AA and NA meetings every week. The Spokane AA Central Office at 1700 W 7th Ave maintains a 24/7 hotline and full meeting schedule. NA meetings are held daily at locations across the city. Visit aaspokane.org or na.org for schedules.

            .accordion-item
              h2.accordion-header#faqH5
                button.accordion-button.collapsed(type="button" data-bs-toggle="collapse" data-bs-target="#faqC5" aria-expanded="false" aria-controls="faqC5")
                  | How long does it take to get sober?
              #faqC5.accordion-collapse.collapse(aria-labelledby="faqH5" data-bs-parent="#faqAccordion")
                .accordion-body
                  | Physical detox typically takes 3–10 days depending on the substance. Recovery is a long-term process. Most treatment programs run 30–90 days, and research shows outcomes improve significantly after 90+ days of sustained treatment. Spokane's recovery community supports people at every stage of the journey.

            .accordion-item
              h2.accordion-header#faqH6
                button.accordion-button.collapsed(type="button" data-bs-toggle="collapse" data-bs-target="#faqC6" aria-expanded="false" aria-controls="faqC6")
                  | What treatment options are available in Spokane?
              #faqC6.accordion-collapse.collapse(aria-labelledby="faqH6" data-bs-parent="#faqAccordion")
                .accordion-body
                  | Spokane offers the full continuum of care: medical detox (STARS, Inland Northwest BH), residential/inpatient treatment (Royal Life Centers, Pioneer Pathways), intensive outpatient programs (Rebuilt Treatment, Riverside Recovery), medication-assisted treatment (Ideal Option, Spokane CTC), and peer support (AA, NA, SMART Recovery, Celebrate Recovery).

            .accordion-item
              h2.accordion-header#faqH7
                button.accordion-button.collapsed(type="button" data-bs-toggle="collapse" data-bs-target="#faqC7" aria-expanded="false" aria-controls="faqC7")
                  | Where can I find sober housing in Spokane?
              #faqC7.accordion-collapse.collapse(aria-labelledby="faqH7" data-bs-parent="#faqAccordion")
                .accordion-body
                  | Options include Oxford Houses (self-governed recovery homes), transitional housing through Catholic Charities and Volunteers of America, and supportive housing through Spokane Housing Authority. Emergency shelters like UGM and House of Charity also provide sober environments. Visit our #[a(href='/shelter-housing.html') Shelter & Housing] page for the full list.

            .accordion-item
              h2.accordion-header#faqH8
                button.accordion-button.collapsed(type="button" data-bs-toggle="collapse" data-bs-target="#faqC8" aria-expanded="false" aria-controls="faqC8")
                  | Does insurance cover rehab in Spokane?
              #faqC8.accordion-collapse.collapse(aria-labelledby="faqH8" data-bs-parent="#faqAccordion")
                .accordion-body
                  | Yes. Under the Mental Health Parity Act, most private insurance and Apple Health (Medicaid) cover substance use disorder treatment including detox, residential, and outpatient care. Read our full guide on #[a(href='/blog/insurance-coverage-rehab-washington.html') insurance coverage for rehab in Washington].

          hr.my-5

          //- Conclusion
          h2#conclusion.mt-5
            i.bi.bi-sun.text-warning.me-2
            | You Can Get Sober in Spokane — Starting Today
          p Getting sober in Spokane is not just possible — it's supported by one of the most comprehensive recovery networks in the Pacific Northwest. From free medical detox to daily support group meetings, from emergency shelter to career rebuilding — every resource you need is within reach, right here in the Inland Northwest.
          p The hardest step is the first one. But you don't have to take it alone.

